  "doc_id": "6161",
  "text": "Because reward context information is constant in a block of trials, monkeys exhibit robust behavioral bias toward the larger-reward target, as reflected in biased choice and reaction time (RT) in free-choice and forced-choice versions of the task, respectively [CITATION_1] . The RT bias can be modulated by the duration of the foreperiod before target appearance, suggesting that the selection process uses not only neural signals reflecting the value of the target, but also reward context-dependent signals present in the foreperiod in the absence of any target information [CITATION_2] . Remarkably, consistent with the foreperiod durationmodulated RT bias, some caudate neurons show reward contextmodulated activity during the foreperiod, with the difference between reward contexts increasing with time before target presentation [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . For example, the neuron in Figure 1C gradually ramped up its activity, reaching a much higher level before target onset in blocks when the contralateral target is paired with the larger reward. This type of activity may contribute to reward context-based bias in the selection process to favor one action in the absence of additional input. Such block-wise, reward context-specific signal that emerges before the appearance of a visual target, is prevalent in the dorsal/central portion of caudate [CITATION_6] .",
